Now generate the verification plan based on the design specification you just created.

This plan will be executed after implementation to verify correctness, reliability, and code quality.

## Required Sections

### 1. Unit Tests
For each module/component in the design:
- Test function name (`test_should_` prefix describing behavior)
- What behavior it verifies
- Input data and expected output
- Edge cases (empty inputs, boundary values, error conditions)

### 2. Integration Tests
End-to-end scenarios testing the feature as a whole:
- Scenario description
- Setup steps (prerequisites, fixtures)
- Actions to perform
- Expected outcomes
- Teardown / cleanup

### 3. Error Case Tests
For each error type in the design:
- How to trigger the error
- Expected error type and message
- Expected system behavior

### 4. Build & Lint Verification
- `cargo build` — zero errors, zero warnings
- `cargo +nightly fmt --check` — no formatting issues
- `cargo clippy -- -D warnings` — no lint warnings
- `cargo audit` — no new security vulnerabilities

### 5. Manual Verification Checklist
- Smoke tests for a human reviewer
- Expected observable behaviors
- Performance sanity checks (if applicable)

### 6. Acceptance Criteria
Numbered checklist of conditions that must ALL be true. Each criterion must be objectively verifiable.

## Output Format

Output a Markdown document. Use checkboxes (`- [ ]`) for verifiable items. Use code blocks for test signatures and commands. Write the file to `.gba/{{ feature_id }}_{{ feature_slug }}/specs/verification.md`.
